## 4. Running the pipeline

**Build → Pipelines → Run pipeline**, then add variables.

### 4.1 The four variables

| Variable | Default | Values | Required? |
|---|---|---|---|
| `RUN_GOVERNANCE` | `false` | `true` | **Always** — nothing runs without it |
| `GOV_MODE` | `verify` | `verify` \| `dryrun` \| `apply` | Only for dryrun/apply |
| `GOV_TARGET_TYPE` | `project` | `project` \| `subgroup` \| `batch` | Only for subgroup/batch |
| `GOV_TARGET` | *(empty)* | id or path | **Always** — no default by design |

`GOV_TARGET` is intentionally mandatory. A default target would let someone
trigger an apply against a hardcoded repo without consciously choosing it. The
pipeline variables are the audit record of what was touched.

### 4.2 Single repo

| Goal | Variables |
|---|---|
| **Verify** | `RUN_GOVERNANCE=true`<br>`GOV_TARGET=2840` |
| **Dry-run** | `RUN_GOVERNANCE=true`<br>`GOV_MODE=dryrun`<br>`GOV_TARGET=2840` |
| **Apply** | `RUN_GOVERNANCE=true`<br>`GOV_MODE=apply`<br>`GOV_TARGET=2840` |

`GOV_TARGET` accepts a numeric project ID (`2840`) or a full path
(`itepaypg-sbiepay2/application/backend/epay_admin_portal_service`).
**Prefer the ID** — paths are case-sensitive and differ between instances.

`GOV_TARGET_TYPE` is not needed; `project` is the default.

### 4.3 Whole subgroup (multiple repos)

| Goal | Variables |
|---|---|
| **Verify** | `RUN_GOVERNANCE=true`<br>`GOV_TARGET_TYPE=subgroup`<br>`GOV_TARGET=itepaypg-sbiepay2/application/backend` |
| **Dry-run** | `RUN_GOVERNANCE=true`<br>`GOV_MODE=dryrun`<br>`GOV_TARGET_TYPE=subgroup`<br>`GOV_TARGET=itepaypg-sbiepay2/application/backend` |
| **Apply** | `RUN_GOVERNANCE=true`<br>`GOV_MODE=apply`<br>`GOV_TARGET_TYPE=subgroup`<br>`GOV_TARGET=itepaypg-sbiepay2/application/backend` |

Subgroup mode:
- includes **nested sub-subgroups** automatically
- **excludes archived** repos
- **lists every repo it found before processing** — read this list; it is your
  last chance to spot a repo you did not intend to touch
- is **FAIL-STOP** — halts on the first repo that errors; the summary shows
  which repos completed so you know where to resume

A numeric group ID also works (e.g. `2793` for Backend).

### 4.4 Batch (list from a file)

Commit a file of project IDs, one per line (`#` comments and blank lines
ignored; inline `# path` comments are stripped):

```
# Backend
2840    # epay_admin_portal_service
2600    # epay_admin_service
```

| Variable | Value |
|---|---|
| `RUN_GOVERNANCE` | `true` |
| `GOV_MODE` | `apply` |
| `GOV_TARGET_TYPE` | `batch` |
| `GOV_TARGET` | `repos_to_apply.txt` |

### 4.5 The apply job is different

- Only appears when `$CI_COMMIT_REF_PROTECTED == "true"` — i.e. a protected branch
- Requires a **manual play click**; it never starts on its own
- From an unprotected branch the job is **not offered at all**

### 4.6 Recommended sequence

```
1. GOV_MODE=verify   ->  what is the current state?
2. GOV_MODE=dryrun   ->  what would change?
3. GOV_MODE=apply    ->  make it so (click play)
4. GOV_MODE=verify   ->  confirm
```

