## 5. Running locally

The same script runs on a workstation. Config is read from environment
variables first, falling back to literals in the CONFIG block.

```bat
REM Windows
set GOVERNANCE_GITLAB_URL=https://gitlab.sbi
set GOVERNANCE_TOKEN=glpat-xxxxxxxx

python311\python.exe apply_repo_governance.py --project 2840 --verify
python311\python.exe apply_repo_governance.py --project 2840 --dry-run
python311\python.exe apply_repo_governance.py --project 2840
python311\python.exe apply_repo_governance.py --subgroup itepaypg-sbiepay2/application/backend --dry-run
python311\python.exe apply_repo_governance.py --batch repos_to_apply.txt
```

| Flag | Effect |
|---|---|
| `--verify` | read current state only |
| `--dry-run` | print every write that would happen |
| *(no flag)* | **apply**, then auto-verify |

Alternatively edit `GITLAB_URL` / `TOKEN` / `TARGET_PROJECT` in the CONFIG
block. **Always confirm the banner reads `Target : https://gitlab.sbi`** —
pointing at the old instance is the most common cause of an unexplained 401,
because tokens are instance-specific.

Each run writes `governance_<repo>_<timestamp>.txt`; multi-repo runs write
`governance_BATCH_<timestamp>.txt`.

